Below is a **cook‑book of concrete, macOS‑specific tricks** that have been used (or could be used) to make a kernel extension (kext) harder to read, debug and statically analyse.  
Each technique is followed by a **minimal, compile‑able snippet** (or pseudocode) that demonstrates the idea.  
All the code is written in the language that the macOS kernel expects – plain C with the IOKit C++‑style base classes – plus a few inline‑assembly fragments where the trick really needs it.

> **Important** – The examples are intended for **research and education only**.  
> Distributing or running an obfuscated kext on a production system may break the System Integrity Protection (SIP), driver‑signing requirements and macOS licensing. Use a VM, disable SIP (`csrutil disable`) and sign the kext with a self‑generated certificate that is added to the system key‑chain.

---

## 1.  Control‑Flow Flattening (CF‑Flatten)

Instead of a classic `if…else` or `switch` the whole routine is reduced to a **state machine** that jumps through a table of function pointers.  The original logical flow is hidden in a big `while (state != DONE)` loop.

### 1.1  Flattened driver start routine (C)

```c
/*--- FlattenedDriverStart.c -----------------------------------*/
/*  Original code:
 *   if (condition)  doA();
 *   else            doB();
 *   doC();
 *   return kIOReturnSuccess;
 */

typedef IOReturn (*state_fn_t)(void *);

static IOReturn doA(void *ctx);
static IOReturn doB(void *ctx);
static IOReturn doC(void *ctx);
static IOReturn finish(void *ctx);

/* The table index is the “state”.  The values are deliberately shuffled. */
static const state_fn_t state_table[] = {
    finish,   /* 0 -> DONE */
    doC,      /* 1 -> run C   */
    doB,      /* 2 -> run B   */
    doA,      /* 3 -> run A   */
};

/* Opaque predicate – always true, but the compiler cannot prove it */
static inline bool opaque_true(uint64_t seed)
{
    return ((seed * 0x9e3779b97f4a7c15ULL) >> 32) == ((seed >> 8) & 0xff);
}

/* Flattened entry point */
static IOReturn FlattenedStart(void *unused)
{
    uint64_t seed = mach_absolute_time();   /* unpredictable at compile‑time */
    uint32_t state = 3;                     /* start with “doA” */

    while (state != 0) {    /* 0 == DONE */
        /* The opaque predicate can be used to insert dead code that looks
         * like a real check.  It also confuses static analysis tools. */
        if (opaque_true(seed)) {
            /* No‑op – just to make the CFG look larger */
            __asm__ volatile("" ::: "memory");
        }

        /* Indirect call – the real work is hidden behind the table */
        state = (uint32_t)(*state_table[state])(&state);
    }
    return kIOReturnSuccess;
}

/* -----------------------------------------------------------------*/
/* The real “worker” functions return the next state (index).  They are
 * deliberately tiny so the flattening table looks plausible. */
static IOReturn doA(void *ctx) { /* …do the original A… */ return 2; }
static IOReturn doB(void *ctx) { /* …do the original B… */ return 2; }
static IOReturn doC(void *ctx) { /* …do the original C… */ return 0; }
static IOReturn finish(void *ctx) { return 0; }
```

*Result*: A static disassembler sees only a monotonous `while` loop with a jump‑table.  The real logical order is only recoverable after you trace the table values at run‑time.

