## 2.  Opaque Predicates & Dead Branches

A predicate that is **always true/false** but whose truth value depends on a value that the compiler cannot resolve (e.g. a value read from a CPU register).  
The dead branch contains a *large amount of bogus code* to bloat the control‑flow graph.

### 2.1  Example (C + inline asm)

```c
static inline bool opaque_pred(uint64_t x)
{
    /* The expression is mathematically always true for any x,
     * but the compiler cannot prove it without heavy algebra. */
    return ((x ^ 0x5A5A5A5A5A5A5A5AULL) + 0xA5A5A5A5A5A5A5A5ULL) == (x + 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFULL);
}

/* A dead branch that looks like legit error handling */
static void dead_path(void)
{
    /* Insert a lot of unrelated syscalls – they will never be taken */
    for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {
        (void)kern_return_t;   /* keep the compiler from removing */
    }
    IOLog("DEAD PATH REACHED: %d\n", 0);
}

/* Real code */
static IOReturn DoSomething(void)
{
    uint64_t ts = mach_absolute_time();

    if (opaque_pred(ts)) {
        /* This is the *real* path – 99% of the time we end up here */
        IOLog("Real work happening\n");
    } else {
        dead_path();           /* never executed, but bloats the CFG */
    }
    return kIOReturnSuccess;
}
```

*Result*: A naïve control‑flow analysis will think both branches are possible, and the dead code may be mistakenly investigated for bugs.

