## 3.  String / Constant Encryption

Hard‑coded identifiers (device names, registry keys, IOCTL numbers) are stored **encrypted** and only decrypted in the driver’s `start` routine.  

### 3.1  Simple XOR‑encrypted string (C)

```c
/* -- encrypted.c ---------------------------------------- */
static const uint8_t enc_name[] = {
    0x3F,0x1A,0x0E,0x54,0x33,0x0A,0x3E,0x5B,0x3C,0x12,0x19,0x6A,0x00   // "com.mydevice"
};

static const uint8_t key = 0x5A;

/* Decrypt at runtime – the buffer is allocated on the stack and never
 * persisted in the binary. */
static char *decrypt_name(void)
{
    size_t len = sizeof(enc_name) - 1;   // exclude terminating 0x00
    char *out = (char *)IOMalloc(len + 1);
    for (size_t i = 0; i < len; ++i)
        out[i] = enc_name[i] ^ key;
    out[len] = '\0';
    return out;
}

/* Use the decrypted name to register the service */
static bool RegisterMyDevice(void)
{
    char *name = decrypt_name();
    bool ok = IOService::publishResource(name);
    IOFree(name, strlen(name)+1);
    return ok;
}
```

*Result*: `strings` on the binary shows only the encrypted byte array; the clear‑text name appears only in RAM after the kext has started.

### 3.2  Encrypted IOCTL tables (pseudocode)

```c
/*   Each IOCTL is stored as {enc_code, enc_handler_offset} */
static const uint32_t enc_ioctls[][2] = {
    { 0xA3B2C1D0 ^ 0x5A5A5A5A, 0x0010 ^ 0x5A5A5A5A },
    { 0xB4C3D2E1 ^ 0x5A5A5A5A, 0x0030 ^ 0x5A5A5A5A },
    /* … */
};

static IOReturn (*handler_table[])(void *) = {
    handler0, handler1, handler2, /* real functions */
};

/* Resolve at runtime */
static IOReturn DispatchIOCTL(uint32_t code, void *data)
{
    uint32_t key = 0x5A5A5A5A;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < ARRAY_SIZE(enc_ioctls); ++i) {
        if ((enc_ioctls[i][0] ^ key) == code) {
            uint32_t idx = (enc_ioctls[i][1] ^ key) >> 4; // simple shuffle
            return handler_table[idx](data);
        }
    }
    return kIOReturnUnsupported;
}
```

*Result*: The driver’s IOCTL surface is not visible in the binary; a static scan merely sees a list of random numbers.

