## 5.  Self‑Modifying Code (SMC)

macOS permits a kext to **write to its own code pages** after they have been marked executable.  This can be used to:

* Patch a routine after a licence check.  
* Replace a jump target with a “NOP sled” when a debugger is detected.

### 5.1  Simple SMC that patches a function after a check

```c
/* ---------------------------------------------------------- */
static void guarded_func(void)
{
    IOLog("Original guarded function – safe path\n");
}

/* The “patch” bytes – a short sequence that just returns kIOReturnSuccess */
static const uint8_t patch_bytes[] = {
    0x48, 0x31, 0xC0,           // xor    rax,rax
    0xC3                        // ret
};

/* Detect a debugger via the kernel debug flag (public API). */
static bool debugger_present(void)
{
    return (kdebug_debugger_present != 0);
}

/* Self‑modify code at runtime */
static void maybe_patch_guarded(void)
{
    if (debugger_present()) {
        /* Compute the address of the function (rounded down to a page) */
        vm_offset_t func_addr = (vm_offset_t)&guarded_func;
        vm_offset_t page = func_addr & ~PAGE_MASK;
        vm_protect(kernel_map, page, PAGE_SIZE,
                   FALSE, VM_PROT_READ|VM_PROT_WRITE|VM_PROT_EXECUTE);

        /* Overwrite the first few bytes with the patch */
        bcopy(patch_bytes, (void *)func_addr, sizeof(patch_bytes));

        /* Restore normal protections (optional) */
        vm_protect(kernel_map, page, PAGE_SIZE,
                   FALSE, VM_PROT_READ|VM_PROT_EXECUTE);
    }
}

/* ---------------------------------------------------------- */
static kern_return_t MyKextStart(void)
{
    maybe_patch_guarded();   // executed once at load time
    guarded_func();          // will do the original or the patched version
    return KERN_SUCCESS;
}
```

*Result*: When a debugger is attached, the first bytes of `guarded_func` are overwritten with a trivial “return‑immediately” routine, making the payload invisible to a static trace that runs without a debugger.

